      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my realtor just mentioned i need to set up an escrow account for the house i'm buying in toronto. i've never heard of that before... what exactly is escrow and why do i need it for the closing?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Escrow, in the context of real estate, is a trust account where funds are held until certain conditions are met, like the transfer of ownership or payment of taxes. It's a way to ensure that payments are made at the right time, and it's a common practice in many countries, including Canada. In Toronto, where the real estate market can be quite active, escrow accounts help prevent disputes and ensure a smooth closing process.\n\nYou'll typically need to set up an escrow account for the closing of your new home because it allows the seller to hold onto funds until the buyer has completed the necessary steps, such as obtaining a mortgage and passing a home inspection. This way, the seller can be confident that the funds will be released when the conditions are met. It's a bit like a temporary holding cell for the funds, but instead of a physical cell, it's a trust account managed by the real estate agent or a third-party escrow service.\n\nNow, I'm not saying it's a bad thing, but it's a bit like a group of goblins guarding the treasure, making sure it's released only when the conditions are met. And, just like how goblins are known to be mischievous, there's",
