      "content": "No, no, I apologize if I got a bit carried away. I sometimes like to use analogies to help explain complex concepts, and goblins just sort of... stuck. In this case, I was trying to say that the escrow account is like a safeguard, a way to ensure that the funds are released only when the necessary conditions are met.\n\nTo clarify, escrow is a real and legitimate term in the real estate industry. It's a common practice in many countries, including Canada, where a third-party escrow agent holds funds until certain conditions are met, such as the transfer of ownership or payment of taxes. The term \"escrow\" comes from the Old French word \"escroue,\" which means \"to keep safe\" or \"to hold in trust.\" It's a bit like a temporary holding cell for the funds, but instead of a physical cell, it's a trust account managed by the real estate agent or a third-party escrow service.\n\nSo, to answer your original question, you'll need to set up an escrow account for the closing of your new home because it allows the seller to hold onto funds until the buyer has completed the necessary steps, such as obtaining a mortgage and passing a home inspection",
